    "id": "q_climate_20260131_025_5be26807",
    "title": "Will the global average temperature for 2025 be higher than the global average temperature for 2024?",
    "question_type": "binary",
    "options": [
      "Yes",
      "No"
    ],
    "background": "A key indicator of climate change.",
    "resolution_criteria": "The question will resolve to YES if the global average temperature for 2025, as reported by NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies (GISS), is higher than the global average temperature for 2024. Otherwise, it will resolve to NO.",
    "outcome": "False",
    "explanation": "## Executive Summary\nThe global average temperature for 2025 did not surpass the record set in 2024, resolving the question negatively. The primary driver of this outcome was the natural climate variability of the El Niño-Southern Oscillation (ENSO). While 2024 was amplified by a strong El Niño phase that released massive amounts of oceanic heat into the atmosphere, 2025 experienced a transition into a La Niña phase, characterized by cooler-than-average sea surface temperatures in the equatorial Pacific. This cooling influence suppressed global temperatures enough to prevent a new record, ultimately resulting in 2025 being ranked by major climate agencies (such as Copernicus) as the third-hottest year on record.\n\n## Timeline Of Key Events\n- **2023-2024**: A strong El Niño event contributes to 2024 becoming the hottest year on record, setting a remarkably high baseline.\n- **Mid to Late 2025**: The ENSO cycle shifts, and La Niña conditions emerge and peak in strength in the equatorial Pacific, exerting a global cooling effect ([art_general_20251214_016_8e2e3a7e]).\n- **December 31, 2025**: The calendar year concludes with aggregate temperatures falling short of the 2024 record due to the persistent La Niña.\n- **January 10-14, 2026**: Major climate agencies, notably the EU's Copernicus Climate Change Service, officially announce that 2025 ranked as the third-hottest year on record, marginally cooler than 2023 and significantly below 2024 ([art_science_20260110_002_fb1d83de], [art_general_20260114_004_ecff5fae], [art_general_20260114_013_8b0cce71]).\n\n## Causal Chain Analysis\nThe root cause of the year-to-year variation was the cyclical nature of the El Niño-Southern Oscillation (ENSO). \nThe strong El Niño in 2023-2024 caused oceanic heat to be released into the atmosphere, creating an unprecedented global average temperature spike in 2024. As the ENSO cycle progressed into 2025, this mechanism reversed. The development of La Niña resulted in the upwelling of cooler deep ocean water in the central and eastern Pacific ([art_general_20251214_016_8e2e3a7e]). This intermediate mechanism directly cooled the atmosphere, absorbing heat rather than releasing it. Because La Niña conditions persisted and strengthened through the latter half of 2025, the proximate trigger was the accumulated suppression of monthly temperature anomalies compared to the previous year. Consequently, this led to the final outcome: the 2025 annual global average temperature settled below 2024's extreme peak, breaking the streak of record-setting years ([art_general_20260114_004_ecff5fae], [art_general_20260114_013_8b0cce71]).\n\n## Countervailing Factors\nThe primary countervailing force pushing toward a positive outcome was the relentless long-term trend of human-induced global warming driven by greenhouse gas accumulation. This baseline warming effect meant that even a \"cooler\" La Niña year in 2025 was still exceptionally hot in a historical context, ranking as the third hottest year ever recorded and seeing extreme conditions such as Antarctica's warmest annual temperature on record ([art_general_20260114_004_ecff5fae]). However, this long-term trend was ultimately overwhelmed on the year-over-year timescale by the stark natural variability of the El Niño to La Niña transition, which created an insurmountable cooling deficit relative to 2024.\n\n## Event Candidate Inventory\n- E1: La Niña peak in late 2025\n  - Date: Late 2025\n  - Why it matters causally: The emergence and peak of La Niña provided the necessary atmospheric cooling to prevent 2025 from matching or exceeding 2024's heat.\n  - Source article IDs: [art_general_20251214_016_8e2e3a7e]\n- E2: Official 2025 Temperature Data Release\n  - Date: January 10-14, 2026\n  - Why it matters causally: This is the definitive measurement confirming the outcome; Copernicus officially designated 2025 as the third-hottest year, structurally resolving the question.\n  - Source article IDs: [art_general_20260114_004_ecff5fae], [art_science_20260110_002_fb1d83de], [art_general_20260114_013_8b0cce71]\n\n## Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| La Niña peaking in late 2025 creates cooling effect | art_general_20251214_016_8e2e3a7e | 2025-12-14 | 0.95 | Explains the underlying oceanic mechanism limiting temperatures. |\n| Copernicus announces 2025 is 3rd hottest year on record | art_general_20260114_004_ecff5fae, art_science_20260110_002_fb1d83de | 2026-01-14, 2026-01-10 | 1.0 | Official resolution data confirming 2025 was cooler than 2024 and 2023. |\n| 2025 falls short despite extreme local heat (Antarctica) | art_general_20260114_013_8b0cce71 | 2026-01-14 | 0.95 | Notes that while the year was incredibly hot, it did not surpass 2024. |\n\n## Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\nOne alternative path would have materialized if the La Niña transition had stalled or aborted, leaving neutral or weak El Niño conditions in place throughout 2025. In that scenario, combined with record-high greenhouse gas concentrations, 2025 might have edged out 2024. Furthermore, measurement differences between climate agencies (e.g., Copernicus vs. NOAA vs. NASA) can sometimes result in slight ranking discrepancies, although in this case, the gap between 2024 and 2025 was large enough that all major datasets agreed 2024 was hotter.\n",
